CONTENT = '''<figure style="margin:1.5em 0 2.5em;">
<img src="/static/blog/illustrations/exhibitionism-psychology.svg" alt="Exhibitionism: the compulsion to be seen — developmental origins, compulsion loop, psychological structure" style="width:100%;border-radius:16px;display:block;">
</figure>

<p>Exhibitionism sits in an uncomfortable position in the clinical literature. It is serious enough to be classified as a paraphilic disorder — a pattern of sexual arousal centred on the exposure of the genitals to non-consenting strangers — yet it is often treated reductively: as a legal problem, a punchline, or at best a symptom without a coherent psychology behind it. The clinical and psychoanalytic literature, when taken seriously, tells a more specific and more illuminating story. Exhibitionism is not random deviance. It is a particular solution to a particular problem — a problem that originates much earlier in development than the sexual behaviour itself.</p>

<h2>What Exhibitionism Actually Is</h2>

<p>The DSM-5 distinguishes between exhibitionistic disorder — the clinical condition — and exhibitionistic interests more broadly. The disorder requires that the paraphilia causes significant distress or involves acting on the urge with non-consenting individuals. The behaviour pattern is remarkably consistent across cases: the exhibitionist exposes himself (the vast majority of clinical cases are male) to a stranger, typically in a public or semi-public setting, and the critical element is not the exposure itself but the reaction it produces. The shock, the alarm, the involuntary response of the victim — that response is what the behaviour is organised around.</p>

<p>This detail is clinically important and often missed. Exhibitionism is not straightforwardly an act of self-display. It is an act of forced reaction-extraction. The exhibitionist is not, in the primary sense, seeking admiration — he is seeking a specific kind of impact. The difference matters enormously for understanding the psychology underneath.</p>

<h2>The Object Relations Framework</h2>

<p>The most coherent psychoanalytic framework for understanding exhibitionism comes from object relations theory, and in particular from the work of theorists in the Winnicottian and Kohutian traditions. Donald Winnicott's concept of mirroring — the idea that the infant's sense of self is fundamentally constituted through being seen and reflected by the primary caregiver — provides the developmental context. A child whose face, when it looks at its mother's face, sees not itself but the mother's mood, the mother's preoccupation, the mother's anxiety, does not develop a secure sense that its existence registers. It learns, at a level that precedes language, that to be visible is uncertain, conditional, unreliable.</p>

<p>Heinz Kohut's self-psychology elaborated this into the concept of the "mirror transference" — the developmental need to have one's emerging self confirmed, reflected back, and validated by a significant other. When this need is adequately met in childhood, it recedes naturally; the person develops a stable enough internal sense of self-worth that they no longer require continuous external confirmation. When it is inadequately met — through parental unavailability, narcissism, abuse, humiliation, or simple emotional absence — the need does not disappear. It goes underground, where it tends to express itself in increasingly distorted and compulsive forms.</p>

<blockquote><p>The exhibitionist is not showing himself. He is demanding that the world acknowledge that he exists — and demanding it in the one way that guarantees a response, however unwanted.</p></blockquote>

<h2>Shame as the Engine</h2>

<p>What distinguishes exhibitionism from other expressions of unmet recognition needs is the specific role of shame in its structure. The clinical literature on exhibitionism consistently identifies shame — not simply low self-esteem or anxiety, but specifically shame — as the affective core of the condition.</p>

<p>Shame is different from guilt in a way that matters clinically. Guilt says: I did something wrong. Shame says: I am something wrong. The guilty person can make reparation. The shamed person has nothing to repair — the defect is in the self, not the behaviour. And because shame is fundamentally about visibility — about being seen as defective, as inadequate, as less than — it generates a paradoxical dynamic: the shamed person is simultaneously terrified of being seen and desperate to be seen in a way that would refute the shame.</p>

<p>This is the psychological engine of exhibitionism. The exhibitionist carries a deep and usually pre-verbal conviction that he is inadequate, invisible, or contemptible. The exposure is an attempted resolution of this conviction — a forced moment in which his existence is undeniable, in which he produces a powerful effect in another person, in which he cannot be ignored. The reaction of the victim — alarm, disgust, horror — may seem antithetical to the need for positive validation, but the clinical understanding is that any powerful reaction confirms existence in a way that no reaction does not. Being seen as monstrous is, at some archaic developmental level, preferable to not being seen at all.</p>

<h2>The Compulsion Loop</h2>

<p>Exhibitionism, once established, follows a compulsive cycle that is structurally similar to other addictive processes. The cycle typically moves through four phases.</p>

<p>First, there is the mounting tension — a period of escalating anxiety, irritability, or a diffuse sense of inadequacy that the person cannot easily name or locate. This tension is often triggered by events that touch on the underlying shame core: a professional setback, a rejection, a perceived slight. The tension builds until it reaches a threshold that the ordinary ego cannot manage.</p>

<p>Second, there is the planning or fantasy phase — the exhibitionist begins mentally rehearsing the behaviour, often with an elaborate internal scenario. This phase provides temporary relief from the tension, but it also escalates the arousal. The fantasy is a rehearsal for the moment of forced recognition.</p>

<p>Third, there is the act itself — characterised by an intense, driven quality that clinical descriptions consistently note. Former exhibitionists describe a state of narrowed consciousness, urgency, and the sense of being propelled by something beyond deliberate choice. The act produces the sought reaction, and the reaction produces a complex mixture of arousal, power, and, critically, momentary relief from the shame-tension.</p>

<p>Fourth, and almost invariably, there is the crash — a wave of shame, guilt, and often self-disgust that follows the act. This shame is qualitatively different from the shame that preceded the act. It is shame about what has been done rather than shame about what one is. But here is the cruel logic of the compulsion: this post-act shame feeds directly back into the underlying sense of defectiveness that drives the behaviour. The person confirms to themselves, once again, that they are inadequate, disturbed, unlovable. The tension begins to build again.</p>

<h2>The Role of Power and Control</h2>

<p>The power dynamic in exhibitionism is frequently underanalysed. The clinical tendency is to focus on the pathology of the perpetrator, and rightly so, but the psychology of the compulsion is not fully legible without understanding what the forced reaction of the victim provides.</p>

<p>The person who produces a powerful involuntary response in another has, in that moment, demonstrated causal efficacy. He has made something happen. He has, briefly, reversed the developmental situation in which his existence produced no reliable response. The exhibitionist who was the child of a depressed, unavailable, or narcissistic parent — who learned that his needs, feelings, and presence produced no consistent effect on the caregiver — discovers in the compulsive behaviour a guaranteed mechanism for impact.</p>

<p>This is why the clinical literature consistently notes that exhibitionists are rarely interested in willing partners, and why consensual exposure — even when available — does not satisfy the compulsion. The consent of the other is precisely what removes the psychological function of the act. What is required is the involuntary, uncontrolled reaction — the evidence that the impact is real and beyond the other's management.</p>

<h2>The Narcissistic Core</h2>

<p>The connection between exhibitionism and narcissistic pathology is one of the most consistent findings in the psychodynamic literature on paraphilias. This does not mean that all exhibitionists present with diagnosable Narcissistic Personality Disorder — they often do not. But the structural features of covert narcissism — the underlying shame, the grandiose fantasy life, the acute sensitivity to perceived slights, the combination of surface withdrawal and internal entitlement — are reliably present.</p>

<p>The Jungian framework, as elaborated particularly by James Hollis and other analytical psychologists working in this area, understands the paraphilia as a Shadow phenomenon. The shadow, in Jungian terms, is the disowned dimension of the personality — in this case, the legitimate need for recognition, vitality, and full visibility that could not be expressed or met in ordinary developmental experience. When the legitimate need is consistently frustrated, it does not simply disappear. It is pushed into the shadow, where it accumulates pressure and eventually seeks expression through increasingly indirect and distorted means.</p>

<p>The exhibitionist's legitimate need — to be seen, to matter, to have an effect, to be acknowledged as a person of significance — is entirely normal. Every human being has this need. The pathology is not in the need itself but in the developmental situation that prevented it from being met in ordinary ways, and in the specific compensatory solution the person developed in response to that failure.</p>

<h2>Developmental Pathways</h2>

<p>The developmental history most commonly associated with exhibitionism in the clinical literature involves one or more of the following configurations.</p>

<p>Parental narcissism or emotional unavailability — a childhood environment in which the child's inner life consistently failed to register on the primary caregiver. The child's excitement, distress, achievement, and need were met with either non-response or the parent's own preoccupations. The child learned that the self as experienced from the inside was not the self as received from the outside.</p>

<p>Early humiliation or shame induction — experiences in which the child was publicly or privately humiliated, exposed, or made to feel that their body, desires, or emotions were disgusting or wrong. This is particularly significant when the humiliation involved physical exposure or sexualised contexts, which may create an associative link between exposure, shame, and arousal that later becomes the template for the compulsive behaviour.</p>

<p>Inconsistent mirroring — a caregiving environment that was neither consistently available nor consistently unavailable, but intermittently responsive. This produces an attachment pattern organised around hyper-vigilance to the caregiver's attentional state and an escalating desperation when the attention is withdrawn. The compulsive seeking of forced attention in adulthood can be understood as a repetition of this early pattern — the escalation to increasingly extreme behaviour in the attempt to produce the response that keeps not coming reliably.</p>

<h2>The Victim's Experience and the Ethical Gravity</h2>

<p>Any clinical discussion of exhibitionism that is worth taking seriously must be clear about what the behaviour is for those subjected to it. Exhibitionism is a sexual assault. It involves the non-consensual imposition of sexual content on a person, typically in a context where they have no means of escape or defence. The clinical literature on victims of exhibitionism documents significant psychological sequelae — anxiety, intrusive memories, hypervigilance in public spaces, and in some cases lasting disruption of the victim's own relationship to public life and visibility.</p>

<p>The psychological account of the exhibitionist's motivations and history is not a mitigation of the harm caused. It is a tool for understanding the behaviour well enough to interrupt it. Clinical compassion for the person who enacts the behaviour is not incompatible with clarity about the violation it represents for those subjected to it. A coherent treatment of exhibitionism has to hold both.</p>

<h2>Treatment and What Actually Helps</h2>

<p>The treatment literature on exhibitionism is more encouraging than public perception of the condition might suggest. The compulsion is not intractable, though it is resistant to treatment approaches that do not address the underlying psychological structure.</p>

<p>Cognitive-behavioural approaches, including covert sensitisation (the systematic pairing of the fantasy sequence with aversive imagery) and relapse prevention frameworks drawn from addiction treatment, produce meaningful reductions in behaviour frequency, particularly when combined with ongoing therapeutic support. But the clinical consensus is that behaviour-focused approaches alone produce brittle gains — the compulsive pressure reduces, but the underlying shame and recognition hunger remains, and tends to seek new outlet.</p>

<p>Longer-term psychodynamic or psychoanalytic therapy, aimed at working through the developmental failures that underlie the compulsion, produces more durable results when the person can engage with it. The therapeutic task involves several interlocking elements.</p>

<p>First, the development of genuine mentalization — the capacity to recognise and name one's own internal states, particularly the shame and inadequacy that precede the compulsive urge. Many exhibitionists have minimal contact with the shame that drives the behaviour; the psychological function of the compulsion is precisely to short-circuit the unbearable internal state before it can be fully experienced. Therapy must build the capacity to sit with that state, to name it, and to survive it without the compulsive discharge.</p>

<p>Second, the construction of a genuine identity — a stable sense of self that does not require continuous external confirmation. This is, in essence, the repair of the developmental deficit that created the recognition hunger in the first place. It is slow work. It involves the therapeutic relationship itself as a corrective relational experience — a sustained encounter with another person who can reflect back the patient's inner life consistently, accurately, and without the distortions of the original caregiving environment.</p>

<p>Third, the development of genuine intimacy — the capacity to be seen voluntarily, in contexts of mutual consent and reciprocal vulnerability. This is what the exhibitionist compulsion is a distorted substitute for. The compulsion extracts a forced reaction from a stranger. Intimacy involves the sustained, chosen visibility that comes with being genuinely known by another person over time. The therapeutic work is to make the latter seem possible and survivable — to lower the developmental terror around real visibility enough that the patient can risk it in actual relationships.</p>

<h2>The Deeper Invitation</h2>

<p>There is a final observation in the clinical literature that deserves to be stated plainly, because it is the one that most consistently surprises practitioners encountering this work for the first time. The exhibitionist's underlying need — to be genuinely seen, to matter, to have an undeniable effect on another person's experience — is not a sick need. It is a universal human need. The pathology is entirely in the means of pursuing it.</p>

<p>When the clinical and developmental conditions are right — when the person can engage with the underlying shame, can begin to build a real self rather than relying on the performed impact, can risk the ordinary vulnerability of being known — what often emerges is not merely the absence of the compulsion but something more: a person who is capable, for the first time, of genuine intimacy. The shadow, when it can be acknowledged and integrated rather than enacted blindly, tends to carry not just the pathological distortion but also the original legitimate vitality that was suppressed along with it.</p>

<p>The person who needed, desperately and destructively, to be seen — when that need is finally met through the slow, unglamorous work of genuine relationship — tends to discover that what they were seeking was available all along. It simply required a self strong enough to ask for it honestly, and relationships safe enough to offer it in return.</p>'''


def create_article(apps, schema_editor):
    Article = apps.get_model('topics', 'Article')
    Pillar = apps.get_model('topics', 'Pillar')

    # Create psychological-origin pillar if it doesn't exist
    pillar, _ = Pillar.objects.get_or_create(
        slug='psychological-origin',
        defaults={'name': 'Mental Illness · Psychological Origin'},
    )

    if Article.objects.filter(slug=SLUG).exists():
        return

    Article.objects.create(
        slug=SLUG,
        title=TITLE,
        summary=SUMMARY,
        content=CONTENT,
        pillar=pillar,
        order=1,
        published=True,
    )


def reverse_article(apps, schema_editor):
    Article = apps.get_model('topics', 'Article')
    Article.objects.filter(slug=SLUG).delete()


class Command(BaseCommand):
    help = 'Load exhibitionism psychology article'

    def handle(self, *args, **options):
        from topics.models import Article, Pillar
        pillar, _ = Pillar.objects.get_or_create(
            slug='psychological-origin',
            defaults={'name': 'Mental Illness · Psychological Origin'},
        )
        if Article.objects.filter(slug=SLUG).exists():
            self.stdout.write('Article already exists')
            return
        Article.objects.create(
            slug=SLUG, title=TITLE, summary=SUMMARY,
            content=CONTENT, pillar=pillar, order=1, published=True,
        )
        self.stdout.write(self.style.SUCCESS(f'Created: {SLUG}'))
